<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-224-892  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 224 892.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  March 1 1990 n1203 p8(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Malaise that underlies roll-out of hospital IT; Why are suppliersso reluctant to bid for NHS pilot site systems? ( informationtechnology, National Health Service)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kaye, Jon.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Two major suppliers decline to bid on a National Health Service(NHS) pilot project involving implementation of computer systemsin hospitals, thereby fueling speculation that the NHS's reformprogram is in serious trouble.andP;  NHS efforts to control health carecosts are predicated upon integrated computer systems, but areport from the University of Manchester expresses doubts aboutthe methods and motives with which such systems are beingintroduced into hospitals.andP;  The Department of Health (DOH) isundertaking two parallel pilot programs in computerization, butsuppliers are refusing to deal with the DOH's ambiguity overbudgets, specifications, and time scales.andP;  There are also concernsabout cultural shifts that computerization will bring to thehealth care sector.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Great Britain. National Health ServiceGovernment AgencyAutomationPilot ProjectsManchester, University of. Institute of Science and TechnologyHealth CareManagement of EDPCost.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>